chunks.chunk: In today's video, we delve into the implications of stock splits, using Google as a prime example. Prior to its last stock split, Google was trading at approximately $2,255 per share, which posed a significant barrier for many investors lacking access to fractional shares. Post-split, the share price dropped to around $112, making it more accessible to a broader range of investors. This accessibility extends to options trading as well; for instance, selling cash secured puts on Google required $220,000 before the split, but only about $11,000 afterward. While stock splits can enhance liquidity and affordability, it's crucial to remember that a stock split alone does not indicate a buy signal.

The first stock on our list is RGC, currently trading at $697 with a staggering 52-week high of $950. Over the past year, RGC has experienced an astronomical increase of over 15,000%, and a 5-year gain of 5,700%. This stock is characterized by extreme volatility, making it essential for traders to exercise caution. RGC operates in the bioscience sector, specifically focusing on neurocognitive disorders and infectious diseases. Recently, the company announced a 38-for-1 forward stock split, which means that for every share held, shareholders will receive an additional 37 shares. Post-split, the share price is expected to adjust to approximately $18.34, significantly increasing the number of shares available to investors while lowering the price per share.

Next on our list is API Group, trading at $48.74 and nearing its 52-week high of $48.88. This stock has seen a 30% increase over the past year and a remarkable 328% over the last five years. API Group specializes in safety and specialty services worldwide, including fire protection and HVAC solutions. The company has announced a 3-for-2 stock split, meaning shareholders will receive one additional half share for every two shares they own. If the current price remains stable, the post-split price is expected to be around $32 per share. This move aims to enhance liquidity and make the stock more accessible, particularly for retail investors, while also facilitating the conversion of preferred shares into common stock.

The third stock on our list is Pega Systems, currently priced at $11 per share with a 52-week high of $113. Over the last year, Pega Systems has appreciated by over 74%, while its 5-year growth stands at 6%. This company focuses on software solutions for customer engagement and digital process automation. Pega Systems is set to execute a stock split on June 23, where shareholders will double their shares—holding one share will result in two shares post-split. Assuming the stock price remains around $100 at the time of the split, the new price per share will be approximately $50. This split is designed to increase liquidity and make the stock more appealing to a wider range of investors.

Finally, we have Interactive Brokers, currently trading at $29 per share with a 52-week high of $236. The stock has seen a nearly 70% increase in the last year and a remarkable 392% over the past five years. As a global online brokerage firm, Interactive Brokers provides access to over 150 global markets and a diverse range of financial instruments. The company has announced a 4-for-1 stock split, meaning shareholders will receive three additional shares for each share they hold. If the stock is trading at around $209 at the time of the split, the adjusted price will be around $52 per share. This split is intended to make the stock more accessible to investors, further enhancing its liquidity.
